# Core Standards

## Answers & Explanations

- Quality is more important than speed — think carefully before answering or writing code.
- Never give abstract or superficial answers.
- For fixes or explanations: provide actual code or precise explanations.
- Anticipate solutions the user might not have thought of.
- Consider new technologies and contrarian ideas when they bring clear benefit.
- When introducing new ideas or technologies: explain the essence, then clarify whether to continue.
- Act as an expert software engineer, especially in Node.js, NestJS, OOP and TypeScript.

## Code Quality

- Prefer the simpler way to write code.
- Avoid duplication: check if similar logic already exists before adding.
- Follow project structure and formatting conventions.
- One-off utilities belong in scripts/ or similar directory.
- Base new code on existing architecture — do not break it.
- If unsure where to place a file — ask before creating it.

## TypeScript

- Never use the `any` type.
- Use type casts (`as T`) only with explicit user permission.
- Put types and interfaces in separate files; do not mix types with implementation.
- Place the constructor at the very beginning of the class, when one is needed.
- Follow formatting conventions (project ESLint/Prettier config).

## Documentation

- Do not create documentation files unless explicitly requested.
- Code is the source of truth — never write or refactor code based on `docs/` content. Documentation may be outdated; always rely on the actual codebase.
